history.content:
EE120/EE147/EECS149 - personal opinion

Highly agree with first post on 120 & 147.  120 (~8-10hrs work/week) is a great introduction to the signals/system part of EE (will tell you whether you are interested in those fields and even if you aren't, its concepts still apply to circuits, robotics, and other fields), and doesn't require 16B knowledge.  147 has a very low workload, is fun, and covers a pretty cool field I didn't know existed before (it was the class that first got me excited about EE).

EE120/EE147/EECS149 - personal opinion

Highly agree with first post on 120 & 147.  120 (~8-10hrs work/week) is a great introduction to the signals/system part of EE (will tell you whether you are interested in those fields and even if you aren't, it's concepts still apply to circuits, robotics, and other fields), and doesn't require 16B knowledge.  147 has a very low workload, is fun, and covers a pretty cool field I didn't know existed before (it was the class that first got me excited about EE).

@Elad Alon  @Anant Sahai  

Elad: Unfortunately I think that all of the classes listed in the student response actually do require 16B.  Out of the three of them, 147 is probably the most likely to be OK (simply because the most relevant parts of 16B would be covered in the beginning of the semester), but in general, I wouldn't recommend trying to do too much "prefetching" by taking upper divs at the same time at 16B.  That said, it really depends on your background - if you'd like, please feel free to ping me directly and we can chat about specific suggestions for you.

Please note BTW that 120 is continuing to evolve, and moving forward is highly likely to be much more strongly leveraging the coverage in 16B.
Could anyone recommend any EE upperdivs that would be manageable to take alongside ee16b?
